^-|CP||FP||at|^B@2^Z@3Bridge information stays with me as long as writing on the sand at the beach. It takes only one soft wave to wash everything away. However, as I get older I become more persistent and keep writing on the sand--reviewing the material over and over. This week I have what Howard wanted to get off his chest|
PG| ***** 108 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As I mentioned at the end of Board 1, I think it is not a particularly good idea for non-experts to play the more confusing 1430, and it is too bad that is the popular method.|
PG| ***** 109 ***** |


AT|

0314 more closely resembles the old fashioned Blackwood you learn as a beginner, and is much more logical to me. In 0314 a lower bid means a lower number of key cards—5 C = 0, 5D = 1, 5H = 2. On the other hand in 1430 the illogical 5C = 1 5D = 0 5H = 2.|
PG| ***** 110 ***** |


AT| 

The only purpose for 1430 is for a very obscure reason covering a situation that rarely comes up. And that reason is, if hearts are trump, and the RKCB response is 5D, there is no way to ask for the HQ without committing to 6H. The argument for 1430 is that responder having 1 key card is more likely than responder having 0 key cards, so from a probability perspective, you will be able to do a queen ask in hearts slightly more often playing 1430. |
PG| ***** 111 ***** |


AT|

To me, the slight increase in probability does not, in fact, justify the extra confusion created by playing 1430. Not only that, but many experts have moved on to another solution. They play, when hearts are trump, 4S is RKCB, and they now use 0314. So, for example, say it goes 1H-P-3H (assume limit raise)-P-4S (RKCB for hearts)-P-4N (0 or 3 key cards). And 1S-P-3S-P-4N-P-5C is now 0 or 3 key cards. BTW, that 4S RKCB convention is part of a treatment known as "Kickback Blackwood".|
PG| ***** 112 ***** |


cp|1|AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*N|cp||at|Now I am sure it is off his chest and it should give Dinwiddies a loud scream.|
